prompt:
  requires:
    - passage
    - source
  optional: []
  format: Markdown
  description: >-
    Scene-bounded, plain-language cultural and narrative background for {{passage}} using {{source}}.
    Purpose: supply concrete, verifiable facts that help visualize the scene for Bodies: setting (place/space, time),
    participants and simple positions, ordered actions and pacing, objects and built environment, distances/routes and
    travel practice/risks, and relevant administrative geography. Include historical background and scholarly findings
    when attested. Quantify when possible. No questions. No interpretation or emotion.

---
NON-NEGOTIABLE GUARDRAILS
- Scene-bounded (not verse-by-verse). Treat each coherent scene/image as a unit.
- Evidence-only: describe what is text-bound or attested in {{source}}; include brief source cues for non-obvious claims.
- Quantify where possible (mi/km, days on foot, population scale, jurisdiction scope).
- Plain English. Short sentences. Concrete nouns and verbs.
- Greek/Hebrew terms only when they clarify tone/action; include transliteration + simple gloss.
- Forbidden: “Imagine…”, reenactment language, application, moral summary, emotions/meaning/stakes, or any questions.

# Bodies‑Ready Facts for {{passage}}

## Guidance for the LLM (DO NOT OUTPUT)
- Output facts only. Do not ask questions. Do not summarize themes or emotions.
- Prioritize anchors the Bodies step can use: setting (place/time), who/where, actions and pacing, objects/structures,
  distances/routes and travel practice/risks, administrative/geographic context, brief language notes that affect what can be pictured.
- Name absences plainly (e.g., “No setting is stated.”). Do not fill gaps with guesses.
- For non-obvious claims add a parenthetical source cue: (Josephus, Ant. …), (BDAG s.v. …), (m. Shabbat …), (Carta Atlas …).

## Scenes and Concrete Anchors

For each coherent scene or image in {{passage}}, use the following subsections (omit any subsection the text does not support):

### [Scene or Image Title]

- Setting
  - Place/space: inside/outside; thresholds; line-of-sight; crowding; terrain/road type if relevant. Cite text phrase.
  - Time-of-day/season if stated or attested; quantify if possible. (Source)

- Participants and simple positions
  - Who is present (named or clearly implied). Do not invent figures.
  - Simple spatial relations: near/far; ahead/behind; seated/standing; room/area if attested. Cite text phrase.

- Actions and pacing
  - Ordered actions from the text (imperatives, movements, speech acts).
  - Pace cues (“immediately,” “by night,” delays); travel timeframe if deducible. Cite text phrase. (Source if needed)

- Objects and built environment
  - Tools/containers/structures mentioned or implied by the text; one-clause function if it helps picture. (Source)

- Distances, routes, and travel practice
  - Approximate distance(s) and common route(s) with walking time in days (assume ~12–20 miles / 20–32 km per day; reduce for family with child, night travel, or caution). (Source)
  - Example (for context; adapt to {{passage}} as applicable): Bethlehem → Egyptian border ≈ 75 miles / 120 km, typically 4–6 days on foot; Bethlehem → interior Egyptian refuge (100–200 miles / 160–320 km) typically 7–12 days depending on destination and pace. (Atlas/itinerary source)
  - Typical travel rhythms and risks (night travel urgency/secrecy; road hazards; escorts/patrols where attested). (Source)

- Walking days (if travel is in view)
  - One line with the best estimate for days on foot to the nearest boundary/destination relevant to the scene; give a range; include assumption/source cue. (Source)

- Risks (if travel is in view)
  - One line naming concrete, attested hazards (e.g., darkness/visibility, exposure, banditry/theft, questioning by authorities); avoid speculation; include source cue. (Source)

- Administrative/geographic context
  - Jurisdictions, town/village scale, proximity to notable sites (mi/km). (Source)

- Language notes
  - Term (original + transliteration): simple gloss; one clause on tone/action if it changes how the scene is seen/heard. (Lexicon/source)

- Hearts-ready cultural cues (plain, attested; DO NOT interpret)
  - Childlessness and social pain (e.g., stigma, loss of honor) — one clause; source cue.
  - Table fellowship boundaries (e.g., Jews/Gentiles not eating together) — one clause; source cue.
  - Honor/shame dynamics tied to public acts (e.g., obedience/disobedience seen) — one clause; source cue.
  - Purity practices affecting inclusion/exclusion (e.g., touch, food laws) — one clause; source cue.
  - Patronage/dependence realities (e.g., who provides protection) — one clause; source cue.
  - Travel risks/needs (e.g., several days on foot; night travel danger) — one clause; source cue.

## Style
- Plain English. Short sentences. Concrete description.
- Evidence-first. Quantify when possible. Name unknowns plainly.
- No emotions, stakes, or meanings. No questions. No reenactment.

---
Mini example (Matt 2:13–15) — DO NOT OUTPUT
- Walking days: Bethlehem → Egyptian border ≈ 4–6 days on foot for a family moving cautiously; Bethlehem → likely refuge inside Egypt ≈ 7–12 days depending on destination and pace. (Carta/itineraries)
- Risks: Night travel reduces visibility; uneven roads increase fall risk; exposure for an infant; opportunistic theft/banditry on major roads; potential questioning by authorities near towns. (Josephus; Roman road/security studies)
